es of anti-Confucian liberalism and anti-liberal Confucianism. The result—Confucian liberalism—is akin to civil liberalism, in that it rests the form of liberal democracy on the content of "Confucian democratic civility." It is also comparable to perfectionist liberalism, endorsing a nondominant concept of the common good surrounded by a set of "Confucian governing and civic virtues."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aConfucianism. 0aLiberalism. 4aAsian Studies : Chinese Religion and Philosophy. 4aAsian Studies : Confucianism. 4aPhilosophy : Comparative Philosophy. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Theory. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2023z978311149193640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143849113440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438491134423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438491134/original  a978-3-11-149193-6  SUNY Press eBook Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles